==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Treasure
<hw>Treas"ure</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>tresor</ets>, <ets>tresour</ets>, F. <ets>tr⟦eacute⟧sor</ets>, L.
<ets>thesaurus</ets>, Gr. <?/ a stone laid up, treasure, probably from
the root of <?/ to put, place. See <er>Thesis</er>, and cf.
<er>Thesaurus</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Wealth accumulated;
especially, a stock, or store of money in reserve.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This <qex>treasure</qex> hath fortune unto us given.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A great quantity of anything collected for future
use; abundance; plenty.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We have <qex>treasures</qex> in the field, of wheat and of barley,
and of oil and of honey.</q> <rj><qau>Jer. xli. 8.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>That which is very much valued.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Ye shall be peculiar <qex>treasure</qex> unto me.</q> <rj><qau>Ex.
xix. 5.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>From thy wardrobe bring thy chiefest <qex>treasure</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Treasure city</b></col>, <cd>a city for stores and
magazines.</cd> <rj><au>Ex. i. 11.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Treasure</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Treasure
<hw>Treas"ure</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Treasured</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Treasuring</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To collect and deposit, as
money or other valuable things, for future use; to lay up; to hoard;
usually with <xex>up</xex>; <as>as, to <ex>treasure</ex> up
gold</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Treasure-house</ent>⟦br⟧
